<h1>Information for Transcribers DRAFT1 </h1>

<p><br />Information for Transcribers [ title heading in bold]<br />This page contains general information and advice about being a transcriber. It is basic information, to get you started.[text bold]<br />Teams and Counties [main heading bold]<br />You will be assigned a Coordinator [coordinator bold text] (C) who will deal with you as a person. Your C will answer questions, monitor your work, and upgrade your skill level as you begin to work with the more difficult census images: your C is your mentor.<br />Your C will be the Coordinator [coordinator bold text] (C) of the County and Census Year for which you initially choose to transcribe. As a C, they manage the data available for transcribing as well as other technical aspects relating to their county and census years. You will need to contact the relevant C when you need more work.<br />Image Server [ sub heading bold text ]<br />We will be setting up an automated system for allocating images for transcription, linked to an Image Server. In the meantime, the C will arrange to send you images to transcribe — the method varies from C to C.<br />Working for more than one county [ sub heading bold text]<br />When you first begin to transcribe for FreeCEN, your County Team and Coordinators will be the same person. If you want to work for a different county, you simply remain with the same County Team, but contact the new Coordinator for work. Each C can see all your work for their county and census years, no matter which County Team you belong to. Your Coordinator can see your work for all counties and all census years. </p>
<p>The database [ sub heading bold text]<br />You need to be familiar with the terms we use to describe the FreeCEN database and how these relate to the transcription files you create. The database itself is simply an organised set of information held on the servers that make FreeCEN work. (You could think of the database as the digital equivalent of a multi-storey building, its rooms filled with filing cabinets that contain transcribed census returns.)<br />FreeCEN has a single database which is organised by Census Year, County, Piece number, [ Census Year, County, Piece number text bold ] and Civil Parish.[Civil Parish text bold][  We use the same Piece numbers as the National Archives.<br />You’ll be using Images of a census — the pages of an Enumerator’s book — as your source, transcribing the data [ data text bold ](information) it contains into a spreadsheet. You can use any spreadsheet program (or app) that you have on your computer.<br />When you have finished, your transcription is then checked by a Proofreader [ Proofreader text bold ] — an experienced Transcriber.<br />The final checks are done by a Validator [ Validator text bold ]who is often the C. Next, your file is uploaded to the FreeCEN Database on the original FreeCEN site (FreeCEN1): the database there is updated once every four weeks. Finally, your file is copied to the database on this new FreeCEN site (FreeCEN2).<br />Once in the database, all the records you transcribed will be available to be found by a Search.</p>
<p>Transcriber Actions [ subheading text bold ]<br />[ paragraph numbered]If you are not logged in, select Members on the Main menu (at the top of every page). Login using your UserID (or email address) and Password. You can avoid the need to type these every time by checking the Keep me logged in box and allowing your browser to save passwords. (Every few months, you will be asked to confirm your current email address — this is to help ensure that we send important messages to the correct address.)<br />[ paragraph numbered] Once logged in, you will see some information about the system status: this is for all members, not only the technical team! You will also see a set of buttons: these are your Actions[ Actions bold text ] — a set of online tools for managing your Profile (see next item) and more.<br />[ paragraph numbered]Profile [ Profile bold text ] is your details.[ your details bold text ] Please make sure that these are kept up-to-date by selecting Edit. [ Edit bold text ] The coloured fields are those that you can edit. Your telephone number is not essential but it is useful if we find that we cannot contact you by email: it is not made public. Alternatively or additionally, please let us have your postal address. It is helpful to have at least your country, so that we can keep time differences in mind when contacting you.<br />[ paragraph numbered]Roadmap [ Roadmap bold text ] takes you to a page detailing how we plan to develop FreeCEN2 over time, with new features and enhancements for Transcribers, Coordinators and Researchers. We welcome feedback on the Roadmap, and comments on how FreeCEN2 is developing.<br />[ paragraph numbered]Once you have selected an Action, you will notice that there is a row of breadcrumbs (links) just under the main menu that guides you back to previously-visited pages. It is a good idea to use the breadcrumb links, rather than your browser's Back button — especially if you have made any edits online. If you do use the Back button, then please reload the page (Ctrl+R on Windows, Cmd+R on a Mac) before you click on any further links.</p>
<p>Problems logging in? [ subheading bold text ]<br />If your UserID is reported as incorrect: [ bold text ]<br />[ bullet point ]Remember that it is case-sensitive: SuperUser is not the same as superuser, for example.<br />[ bullet point ]If you can’t get your UserID accepted, try using your email address instead. Once you are logged in, check the details of your UserID in your Profile.<br />[ bullet point ]Use the password reset request link to reset your password if necessary. Please note that the activation email sent to you is only valid for 24 hours — if you miss this, you will need to request a reset again.<br />[ bullet point ]If neither UserID or email address is working for you, contact your Coordinator. Please help them by explaining what you have already tried.<br />If you get no message,[ bold text ] then either your Profile is marked as Inactive or you are using the wrong password. Ask your SC to check your Profile and mark you as active.<br />Problem with password reset request? [ subheading bold text ]<br />If you have requested a password reset, but have not received the email, then please ask your SC to make the request for you.</p>
<p>Sending messages [ subheading bold text ]<br />To avoid overloading us with messages, please follow these guidelines<br />[ bullet point ] If your message is about improvements to the system, [ bold text ]please look at the Roadmap to see if we already have it on the to-do list. If it is not there and: <br />[ bullet point with indent ]If the improvement is for version 1.3 (improvements for transcribers), please tell us your idea via the Contact page, with full details of what is needed.<br />[ bullet point with indent ] If the message is about an improvement for researchers (version 1.4), please use the feedback form, which will open in a new tab. <br />[ bullet point ] If the message is about a bug or system failure, ask your Coordinator (C) to trouble-shoot for you. If they can't help, please use the Report a Problem button at the bottom right of all screens (when you are logged in).<br />[ bullet point ] All queries about data need to go to the relevant C: use the Contact page, selecting Data Question on that form.<br />[ bullet point ] Everything else needing a response should go to our Contacts Coordinator: go to the Contact page and select the appropriate category (type) on that form. Please remember to include your UserID and as many details as possible: having to get back to you to ask for them takes us time.</p>
